re that the function exists. For example: ";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"e1e8e324c6a2425a15a5a6cf64ca1290";}i:2386;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:24:"Instead of writing this:";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"6e5bf1343db94ec9fb363298475d3a52";}i:2387;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:18:"we can write this:";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"ce8ddba17826e4e398ee5e96ff90363c";}i:2388;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:180:"The first method works fine, but PHP will throw an error if the plugin is not installed or otherwise available. So to avoid the site-breaking error, the second method is preferred.";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"060413202723603ba0b28e5c34ec08e1";}i:2389;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:29:"Force Forms to Clear Contents";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"f40c996a21f16216b6f3841a6170d1fb";}i:2390;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:205:"If you are savvy with CSS, it is trivial to style forms however and get them to clear preceding/parent elements. If you&rsquo;re new to the game and just want a sure-fire way to get form fields to line up ";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"face676fc867f23bfbd0297b44c1c1b9";}i:2391;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:86:"and look right, here is a well-known snippet of HTML/CSS that you can add to any form:";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"53b3ca78c9e751fb7533e46a71e5ad46";}i:2392;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:55:"Just add that snippet after the last item in your form.";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"d565a1aa16969d54726471e3fb6be56d";}i:2393;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:167:"It&rsquo;s not exactly best-practices design-wise, but it&rsquo;s pretty much guaranteed to do the job. Then later on you can replace the snippet with some proper CSS.";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"808546c0b584253c6e770dc8abfd787c";}i:2394;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:28:"Minimum Posting Requirements";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"453c86c84e8351ae857e03d9e51bedea";}i:2395;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:209:"There are basically four types of USP Forms: user-registration, content posting, contact form, and combo registration/posting. The minimum form requirements (in terms of input fields) for the contact form are ";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"93c6fbcad79df3d5d6360510ab5805bc";}i:2396;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:215:"email, subject, and content. The minimum requirements for user registration are name and email address. The minimum for content posting is the content/textarea field. For the combo registration/posting, the minimum ";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"de18548eff56e5bd270b862fcc4854ec";}i:2397;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:148:"requirements are determined by the plugin settings. Likewise, other requirements may vary depending on how the plugin settings have been configured.";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"782b5c506394033d1eac23bc5234e8b7";}i:2398;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:21:"Shortcodes in Widgets";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"6f55b1dd932854cf64059ebddabdac28";}i:2399;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:123:"By default, shortcodes do not work when included in widgets. To make them work, just add this snippet to your theme&rsquo;s";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"2b87ad43e915f28ebeaf6fb14be69670";}i:2400;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:5:"file:";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"4acf074d67fff178ea8ebb4ede81e115";}i:2401;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:81:"Nothing more to do, but remember to re-add the snippet if/when you change themes.";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"2694de10cb959530652be24836736c71";}i:2402;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:24:"On Install, On Uninstall";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"e80f653e316ad0019a0b9bddd3977c55";}i:2403;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:209:"Just FYI: when USP Pro is installed it creates four new options in the wp_options table. That&rsquo;s it. No new database tables are created. While the plugin is active, new content (post data, user info) may ";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"3d0ac91ea32154d04f46d935d1421b32";}i:2404;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:205:"be added to the database, but no other changes are made anywhere by the plugin. Lastly, when the plugin is uninstalled (deleted from the server), the four options it created are removed from the database. ";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"95d642526d95f3d0d8fc12f02bf29fda";}i:2405;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:173:"Note that the plugin does not delete any posted/submitted content or registered users. If any posts or users were added, it is up to the admin whether or not to remove them.";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"df87b45e9a21af559fd2ce6225a4b80a";}i:2406;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:27:"Alternate Way to Reset Form";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"4258e27d710abecd44d54364de06a659";}i:2407;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:126:"USP Pro includes a shortcode/quicktag for a link that will reset the form. To use a button instead, add this code to any form:";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"6e4fa658b5a82f851ee3fb6091b6dd7b";}i:2408;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:149:"Note that the shortcode requires the form URL as one of its attributes, but the reset <code>&lt;input&gt;</code> tag works without requiring any URL.";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"16a62eded9c2d4400e0b3e22d40d5ba6";}i:2409;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:20:"Custom Field Recipes";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"8d1f64f54ad3b799f4eeb06292e540d1";}i:2410;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:179:"USP Pro provides unlimited custom fields that may be configured to be virtually any type of input field. Here is a list of custom-field recipes for various types of form elements:";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"edfff79eae4478f0af4e03147580365a";}i:2411;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:18:"Add a Select Field";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"8a8cb06f3a31588376257e022223dfc5";}i:2412;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:111:"To add a <code>&lt;select&gt;</code> field to any USP Form, include the following code and customize as needed:";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"ee958347dd0d4e81885be6ba1213628d";}i:2413;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:146:"Note that as written, this example creates a single-item select field. To create a multiple-item select field, just change the first line to this:";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"0fdb37995cf7d37fdd9f981c1e47750c";}i:2414;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:76:"Then to make it a required form field, add this line after the select input:";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"9e215ab17f27150ae7f4375bf1337e42";}i:2415;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:150:"Other markup/tags may be added as needed; for example, you may want to add a <code>&lt;fieldset&gt;</code> and/or <code>&lt;label&gt;</code> element. ";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"18295941b7f010505d250af298a2434b";}i:2416;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:151:"The key thing to keep in mind is that the select tag&rsquo;s name must correspond with an existing custom form field (e.g., <code>usp-custom-1</code>).";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"d1f60b2815ca8607ea5eba2d1f681fe3";}i:2417;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:35:"Custom CSS and JavaScript for Forms";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"58d652db7dc203684ae1fbbeebb290c6";}i:2418;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:197:"Via the &ldquo;CSS/JS&rdquo; settings tab, it&rsquo;s possible to add custom CSS and/or JavaScript to all USP Forms. It&rsquo;s also possible to add CSS/JS on a per-post basis using custom fields. ";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"1eb7a924f67ee840308437bd54ea7b46";}i:2419;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:210:"For example, to add some custom JavaScript to a form, create a new custom field named &ldquo;usp-js&rdquo; and add your JavaScript code. Likewise for CSS, just create a custom field named &ldquo;usp-css&rdquo; ";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"48916c84e1a7f4304b47954485a9638c";}i:2420;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:202:"and add whatever CSS is required. Note that custom CSS is automatically wrapped with <code>&lt;style&gt;</code> tags and custom JavaScript is automatically wrapped with <code>&lt;script&gt;</code> tags.";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"40f877db11e1e78a4840a60a3cbce83a";}i:2421;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra";N;s:3:"org";s:35:"Custom CSS and JavaScript for Posts";s:3:"ctx";s:32:"d013bf004b68ac7ad25aca639b2d32d1";}i:2422;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:3:"tra